\nOn election night, Dewey, his family, and campaign staff confidently gathered in the Roosevelt Hotel in New York City to await the returns.(Ross, p. 241) President Truman - aided by the Secret Service - sneaked away from reporters covering him in Kansas City and rode to nearby Excelsior Springs, Missouri, a small resort town. There he took a room in the historic Elms Hotel, had dinner and a Turkish bath, and went to sleep.(Ross, p. 242) As the votes came in, Truman took an early lead which he never lost. However, the leading radio commentators, such as H. V. Kaltenborn of NBC, confidently predicted that once the \late returns\" came in Dewey would overcome Truman's lead and win. At midnight